{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496888"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:58:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:58:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1428"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1428","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1428"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.4,0.02,0.13,0.28]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1428"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114831"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1428","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1428"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1428"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96835"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1569"},{"type":"tags","id":"2228"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"884"},{"type":"contributions","id":"908"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6047"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9772"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9835"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11569"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12742"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15220"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35813"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40128"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42316"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43081"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44343"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45425"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114831"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department complaining of fever, a new productive cough with purulent rusty brown coloured sputum and shortness of breath. He has also been having nausea and vomiting. He is otherwise well and takes no regular medications. He is from a metropolitan area, with no recent travel overseas or to northern Australia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he is orientated, his temperature is 39.5 degrees C, he has a blood pressure of 100/75 mmHg, pulse of 129/min, respiratory rate of 24/min and oxygen saturation of 92% on room air. Respiratory examination reveals crackles and bronchial sounds over the left lower lung field. Cardiac examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest X-ray is ordered and shows consolidation in the left lower lobe. A venous blood gas (VBG) shows a pH of 7.4 and blood lactate of 1.5 mmol/L. A urea, electrolytes and creatinine and liver function test is ordered, with urea and albumin within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate course of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Discharge the patient home with oral amoxicillin","Admit the patient for oral amoxicillin and oral doxycycline","Discharge the patient home with oral doxycycline","Admit the patient for IV piperacillin/tazobactam","Admit the patient for IV benzylpenicillin and doxycycline"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features of community-acquired pneumonia, including fever, productive cough, dyspnoea, and radiological evidence of left lower lobe consolidation. The presence of systemic symptoms such as nausea and vomiting is significant, as it may limit the ability to tolerate oral medications and indicates a more severe illness. \u003Cstrong\u003EAdmit the patient for IV benzylpenicillin and doxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate option, as intravenous antibiotics are indicated for moderate-severity pneumonia in patients with systemic symptoms or inability to reliably take oral therapy. This regimen provides coverage for common pathogens, including \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E and atypical organisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDischarge the patient home with oral amoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for low-severity pneumonia in a person who is systemically well and able to tolerate oral therapy, which is not the case here due to the patient\u0027s tachycardia, tachypnoea, hypoxaemia, and vomiting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmit the patient for oral amoxicillin and oral doxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered in moderate cases if the person can reliably take oral medications and is not vomiting, but this patient has ongoing nausea and vomiting, making oral therapy unreliable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDischarge the patient home with oral doxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate given the severity of symptoms, abnormal vital signs, and inability to tolerate oral medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmit the patient for IV piperacillin/tazobactam\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for severe pneumonia or when there is suspicion of resistant gram-negative organisms, such as in people with recent travel to northern Australia or risk factors for \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E. This patient has no such risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESeverity assessment tools such as CURB-65 and SMARTCOP are useful in guiding management decisions, but they do not replace clinical judgement. In this case, the patient\u0027s abnormal vital signs and inability to tolerate oral therapy are key factors supporting admission and intravenous antibiotics, even if the calculated score is not high. Always consider the whole clinical picture, including red flags and the person\u0027s ability to take oral medications, when making management decisions for community-acquired pneumonia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Severity assessment tools such as CURB-65 and SMARTCOP support, but do not replace, clinical judgement in community-acquired pneumonia.","Moderate community-acquired pneumonia with systemic symptoms and inability to tolerate oral therapy requires hospital admission and intravenous antibiotics.","Recent travel to northern Australia is an important consideration in empiric antibiotic selection for community-acquired pneumonia."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd. Community-acquired pneumonia in adults [Internet]. 2025.","Charles PGP, Wolfe R, Whitby M, et al, Australian Community-Acquired Pneumonia Study Collaboration, M. Lindsay Grayson, SMART-COP: A Tool for Predicting the Need for Intensive Respiratory or Vasopressor Support in Community-Acquired Pneumonia, Clinical Infectious Diseases, Volume 47, Issue 3, 1 August 2008, Pages 375\u2013384, https://doi.org/10.1086/589754 Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18558884/","Lim WS, van der Eerden MM, Laing R, et al. Defining community acquired pneumonia severity on presentation to hospital: an international derivation and validation study. Thorax. 2003;58(5):377-82, doi: 10.1136/thorax.58.5.377 Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12728155/","Community acquired pneumonia (adults) clinical guideline. SA Health. Updated April 2021. Accessed July 12, 2024. https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/9da8d680432af0a6a631f68cd21c605e/CAP+Clinical+Guideline+%28Adults%29_v2_FINAL_Jan2021+%282%29.pdf?MOD=AJPERES\u0026amp;CACHEID=ROOTWORKSPACE-9da8d680432af0a6a631f68cd21c605e-oqwEVZ9"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96835"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1428"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19449"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19449"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0d43c27d-a543-4033-8fd8-99f2ca10455b.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0d43c27d-a543-4033-8fd8-99f2ca10455b.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":323,"height":204}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96835"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-20T17:44:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-20T17:44:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1428"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114831"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2